me>BRIGHTMAN</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG009104%2F1"><gtr:id>EDDC3690-A0D7-4D0E-98FB-349D7A738BD7</gtr:id><gtr:title>Modes of appropriation: ecology and the politics of property in Amazonia</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G009104/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The purpose of Dr Brightman's postdoctoral research project is to understand changing forms of property in Amazonia. It addresses questions about ownership of resources, and raises more fundamental questions about cultural variations in the definition of property itself. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project is based upon his previous field research among the Akuriyo, Trio and&amp;nbsp; Wayana of southern Suriname and French Guiana. These are Carib-speaking Amerindians who live from small-scale, shifting&amp;nbsp; agriculture, hunting, fishing and the gathering of forest products. The fellowship project will address problems related to the exchange of plant knowledge and to land disputes (particularly those due to the attraction of mineral resources). &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In particular,&amp;nbsp;it will apply recent anthropological theories of property to developments in the study of indigenous plant knowledge and use in Amazonia, focusing on cases in which plant knowledge is turned into a commodity through cross-cultural economic exchanges. Drawing on the anthropology of religion, law, politics and economics,&amp;nbsp;it will analyse the tension between&amp;nbsp; indigenous and market perspectives on these processes of changing property relations to produce publications and a proposal for a research grant for a larger project to develop&amp;nbsp;the work further.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>78868</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/G009104/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>4511FB20-8392-418E-809D-7701FACC03C9</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Law &amp; legal studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D2